-- Seed: Planning Workflow skill
-- Provides explicit ADR + Implementation Plan creation procedure for agents

INSERT INTO skills (id, name, description, content) VALUES (
    'bbbb0001-0000-0001-0002-000000000001',
    'Planning Workflow',
    'Step-by-step procedure for creating ADR + Implementation Plan pairs',
    E'## How to Create a Plan\n\nA Plan consists of two artifacts stored together: an ADR (Architecture Decision Record) and an IMPL doc (implementation plan). They are linked by a shared `chain_id`.\n\n---\n\n### Step 1: Research first\n\nBefore writing anything:\n- `list_artifacts(artifact_type: "adr")` — read existing ADRs so you don''t contradict them\n- `list_artifacts(artifact_type: "iplan")` — check if a plan for this already exists\n- Read relevant source files to understand existing patterns and constraints\n\nNever propose something that duplicates or contradicts existing decisions.\n\n---\n\n### Step 2: Draft the ADR (skip if routine work)\n\nRequired when the feature involves: database schema, API contracts, auth model, storage strategy, technology selection, performance trade-offs, or state management.\n\n**A great ADR contains:**\n- **Context**: One sharp paragraph framing the problem\n- **Alternatives**: Real options with honest trade-offs (not strawmen)\n- **Decision**: The chosen approach with explicit reasoning\n- **Consequences**: What becomes easier and what becomes harder\n\n**Process:**\n1. Draft the ADR as a markdown block in your reply\n2. Ask the user: "Does this decision look right? Any changes before I save it?"\n3. Wait for explicit approval — do NOT call `create_artifact` on an unseen draft\n4. Once approved: `create_artifact(artifact_type="adr", scope="global", title="ADR: <topic>", content="<full ADR>")`\n5. Save the returned `chain_id` — you will pass it to the IMPL doc\n\nSkip the ADR for routine feature work that clearly follows established project patterns.\n\n---\n\n### Step 3: Draft the IMPL doc\n\nRequired for every feature — even small ones.\n\n**A great IMPL doc contains:**\n- **What**: What is being built (one sentence)\n- **Why**: Why this is needed (one sentence)\n- **Key Decisions**: Reference the ADR if one exists\n- **Tasks**: Specific, concrete, executable tasks — not "implement X" but "Add `artifact_id UUID REFERENCES context_artifacts(id)` column to `task_groups` via migration"\n- **Definition of Done**: A checklist a coder can check off\n\n**Process:**\n1. Draft the IMPL doc as a markdown block in your reply\n2. Ask the user: "Does this cover everything? Ready to save the Plan?"\n3. Wait for explicit approval\n4. Once approved:\n   - If there is an ADR: `create_artifact(artifact_type="iplan", scope="global", title="<feature name>", content="<full IMPL>", chain_id=<adr.chain_id>)`\n   - If no ADR: `create_artifact(artifact_type="iplan", scope="global", title="<feature name>", content="<full IMPL>")`\n5. The ADR + IMPL doc now appear as a single Plan card in the Plans panel\n\n---\n\n### Step 4: Confirm\n\nSay: "Plan created: [title] — visible in the Plans panel. Create a task group from it when ready to execute."\n\n---\n\n### Rules\n\n- **Research before writing.** Never propose without checking existing ADRs, plans, and code.\n- **Draft in chat, wait for signoff, then save.** Never call `create_artifact` on a first draft.\n- **Be direct.** State your recommendation clearly. Don''t offer five options when one is right.\n- **Tasks must be executable.** A coder should implement each task without needing clarification.\n- **chain_id links ADR to IMPL.** Always use the ADR''s chain_id when creating the IMPL.'
);

